Implements steno stroke mechanics for count-bank expansion: turning a construct's numeric parameter count into a merged, canonically-ordered stroke. This is the piece that turns e.g. `STKWR-PBGS/-FLT` with count 3 into `STKWR-PBGS/AOFLT` — merging a separate "count bank" sub-stroke into the preceding stroke and re-rendering per canonical English steno key order, rather than just concatenating text.

The module is a thin aggregator over two submodules, `bank` and `keys`, and carries no logic itself; all behavior lives in those files. `keys` owns the key-set model and stroke parsing/rendering: `KeySet`, `StrokeKeys`, `parse_stroke`, `render_stroke`, plus the three ordering tables `LEFT_ORDER`, `MID_ORDER`, `RIGHT_ORDER` that define canonical order `# | S T K P W H R | A O * E U | F R P B L G T S D Z`. `bank` owns the count-bank domain: `CountBank`, `CountBit`, `Side`, and the functions `count_bank`, `add_key`, `apply_count`, `merge_strokes` that build a bank, add keys to it, apply a count value to select which keys are active, and merge the resulting bits into a host stroke.

Non-obvious rule callers must respect: the hyphen in stroke notation is purely a separator for right-bank keys when no middle key (vowel or `*`) is present — its presence/absence in `render_stroke` output depends on whether a middle key was rendered, not on any explicit hyphen state carried in the data. Any code constructing or comparing rendered strokes must go through `render_stroke`/`parse_stroke` rather than string-splicing, since the canonical order and hyphen placement are non-trivial to reproduce by hand. Other crates/modules that consume stroke output should treat `keys` and `bank`'s re-exports here as the complete public surface of stroke mechanics — nothing else in the submodules is public.